canonical:
  title: 盧山三笑
  author: 李齊賢
  language: lzh
  text: 釋道於儒理本齊強將分別自相迷三賢用意無人識一笑非關過虎溪
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 盧山三笑
  author: 李齊賢
  language: lzh
  text: 釋道於儒理本齊。強將分別自相迷。三賢用意無人識。一笑非關過虎溪。
korean:
  title: 여산삼소
  author: 이제현
  language: kor
  text: |-
    불ㆍ도ㆍ유의 이치가 본래 같은데
    억지로 분별하여 스스로들 미혹하네
    세 사람의 뜻을 사람들은 모르나니
    한 번의 웃음이 호계를 지나간 것과는 관계가 없다
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0240_010_0100&viewSync=OT
  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 여산삼소(盧山三笑) : '
    value: ‘이 밑의 네 절구(絶句)는 국재(菊齋)의 횡파십이영(橫坡十二詠) 중의 사수(四首)에 화답한 것이다.’라는 제주(題註)가 있다.
english:
  title: Three Smiles at Lushan
  author: Lee Jae-hyun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The teachings of Buddha, Tao, and Confucius share one essence,
    Yet forced distinctions cloud the minds of those who divide them.
    Few understand the meaning hidden in three sages' hearts—
    One laugh has nothing to do with crossing Tiger Creek.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This poem is part of a series responding to works from the 'Twelve Verses of Horizontal Wave' by Gukjae. The reference to 'three sages' alludes to the legendary meeting at Lushan where a Buddhist monk, a Daoist, and a Confucian scholar famously laughed together in perfect understanding, transcending sectarian boundaries. The 'Tiger Creek' reference evokes the classical anecdote of crossing the creek as a metaphor for departing from worldly concerns.
